# 🏷 Types of Dependency Injection

Spring supports three types:

## 1️⃣ Constructor Injection

Dependencies are injected through the constructor.

```java id="jlwm5"
@Component
class Engine {

}

@Component
class Car {

    private final Engine engine;

    public Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }

}
```

### Advantages

* Immutable Objects
* Easy Testing
* Recommended by Spring

---

## 2️⃣ Setter Injection

Dependencies are injected using setter methods.

```java id="jlwm6"
@Component
class Car {

    private Engine engine;

    @Autowired
    public void setEngine(
            Engine engine) {

        this.engine = engine;

    }

}
```

### Advantages

* Optional Dependencies
* Flexible Configuration

---

## 3️⃣ Field Injection

Dependencies are injected directly into fields.

```java id="jlwm7"
@Component
class Car {

    @Autowired
    private Engine engine;

}
```

### Disadvantages

* Difficult to Test
* Hidden Dependencies
* Not Recommended

---

# 📊 Constructor vs Setter vs Field Injection

| Feature             | Constructor | Setter | Field |
| ------------------- | ----------- | ------ | ----- |
| Recommended         | ✅           | ⚠️     | ❌     |
| Immutable           | ✅           | ❌      | ❌     |
| Easy Testing        | ✅           | ✅      | ❌     |
| Optional Dependency | ❌           | ✅      | ❌     |

